# üöÄ feature request

### Relevant Package

This feature request is for `@angular/core`.


### Description

Currently, the `AsyncPipe` uses `null` a possible return type, for a better `strictNullChecks` support , it should return `undefined`.

```
export declare class AsyncPipe implements OnDestroy, PipeTransform {
  // ...
  transform<T>(obj: Observable<T> | null | undefined): T | null;
  transform<T>(obj: Promise<T> | null | undefined): T | null;
}
```

To work around this, components that have an optional `@Input()` property have to define the possible types as `T | null | undefined`, instead of just using `T | undefined`.


### Describe the solution you'd like

Add `undefined` as a possible return type for the `transform()` method, but keep `null` as the actual value and add a deprecation message.

And in a new major version, update the pipe to return `undefined` instead of null.

```
export declare class AsyncPipe implements OnDestroy, PipeTransform {
  // ...
  transform<T>(obj: Observable<T> | null | undefined): T | undefined;
  transform<T>(obj: Promise<T> | null | undefined): T | undefined;
}
```

# üöÄ feature request

### Relevant Package

- @angular/core


### Description

I would like to combine multiple input properties together. When a component has a lot of input properties and you want to pass all of them to child components, you need to manually add them where ever components need them and need to remember where you're passing them if you want to add new props.

I have a Card component which receives a lot of input properties and I do not want to use a single config property (which sure would solve this issue) for readability in this case:

```html
<app-card
        [id]="item.id"
        [type]="item.type"
        [theme]="item.theme"
        [image]="item.image"
        [title]="item.title"
        [description]="item.description"
        [timeline]="item.timeline"
        [location]="item.location"
        [categories]="item.categories"
        [collection]="item.collection"
        [joined]="item.joined"
      ></app-card>
```

Internally I use a directive that creates the correct child component for me based on the type and theme prop. Currently, I need to pass all the above props the same way down to the child component. When I now want to add a new prop it needs to be added in four places: card component* (`<app-card>`), card directive (2 times), the interface and actual card component* (based on type and theme prop).

*where I also need to specify the type again

```ts
import { Component, Input, OnInit } from '@angular/core'

@Component({
  selector: 'app-card',
  templateUrl: './card.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./card.component.scss'],
})
export class CardComponent implements OnInit {
  @Input('id') id: any // not the real type, just demo here
  @Input('type') type: any
  @Input('theme') theme: any
  @Input('image') image: any
  @Input('title') title: any
  @Input('description') description: any
  @Input('timeline') timeline: any
  @Input('location') location: any
  @Input('categories') categories: any
  @Input('collection') collection: any
  @Input('joined') joined: any

  ngOnInit() {
  }
}
```

```html
<ng-container 
[id]="id"
[type]="type"
[theme]="theme"
[image]="image"
[title]="title"
[description]="description"
[timeline]="timeline"
[location]="location"
[categories]="categories"
[collection]="collection"
[joined]="joined"
cardTheme></ng-container>
```

```ts
// ...
@Directive({
  selector: '[cardTheme]',
})
export class CardDirective implements OnChanges, OnInit {
  @Input() theme: CardTheme
  @Input('id')
  @Input('type')
  @Input('theme')
  @Input('image')
  @Input('title')
  @Input('description')
  @Input('timeline')
  @Input('location')
  @Input('categories')
  @Input('collection')

  // ....

  setInstanceParams() {
    this.component.instance.id = id
    this.component.instance.type = type
    this.component.instance.theme = theme
    this.component.instance.image = image
    this.component.instance.title = title
    this.component.instance.descriptio = descriptio
    this.component.instance.timeline = timeline
    this.component.instance.location = location
    this.component.instance.categories = categories
    this.component.instance.collection = collection
  }
}
```

### Describe the solution you'd like

In the below code you see Input decorators chained together and stored into a single object. This allows me to 1) have better typings here, 2) pass them easier to where ever I want them, 3) better handling of optional types (Card consist of a few theme component specific interfaces) and 4) easier manipulation in my directive because I can simply pass the config prop to it and don't need to care about forgotten props I haven't passed to it.

```ts
import { Component, Input, OnInit } from '@angular/core'

import { Card } from './card.interface'

@Component({
  selector: 'app-card',
  templateUrl: './card.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./card.component.scss'],
})
export class CardComponent implements OnInit {
  @Input('id')
  @Input('type')
  @Input('theme')
  @Input('image')
  @Input('title')
  @Input('description')
  @Input('timeline')
  @Input('location')
  @Input('categories')
  @Input('collection')
  @Input('joined')
  config: Card

  ngOnInit() {
    console.log(this.config)
  }
}
```

